=========================================================
std::lock_guard (C++11) - Interview Notes
=========================================================

What is std::lock_guard?
---------------------------------------------------------

std::lock_guard is a C++11 RAII wrapper around a mutex.

It automatically locks the mutex when the lock_guard object
is created and automatically unlocks it when the object goes
out of scope.

=========================================================
Why do we need lock_guard?
=========================================================

Using lock() and unlock() manually is error-prone.

If unlock() is forgotten or an exception occurs before
unlock(), the mutex remains locked, leading to deadlocks.

lock_guard automatically releases the mutex.

=========================================================
Manual Locking
=========================================================

m.lock();

// Critical Section

m.unlock();

=========================================================
Using lock_guard
=========================================================

std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(m);

// Critical Section

// Automatically unlocks when 'lock' goes out of scope.

=========================================================
Example
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
#include <mutex>

using namespace std;

mutex m;
int counter = 0;

void increment()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100000; i++)
    {
        lock_guard<mutex> lock(m);

        ++counter;
    }
}

int main()
{
    thread t1(increment);
    thread t2(increment);

    t1.join();
    t2.join();

    cout << counter << endl;
}

=========================================================
Advantages
=========================================================

✔ Automatic locking and unlocking.
✔ Exception-safe.
✔ Prevents forgetting unlock().
✔ Uses RAII.

=========================================================
Limitations
=========================================================

✘ Cannot unlock manually.
✘ Cannot lock again.
✘ Cannot transfer ownership.

For these features, use std::unique_lock.

=========================================================
Interview Questions
=========================================================

Q. What is lock_guard?

A lock_guard is a lightweight RAII wrapper that automatically
locks a mutex on construction and unlocks it on destruction.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Why is lock_guard preferred over lock()/unlock()?

Because it automatically releases the mutex, making the code
safer and exception-safe.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. What design principle does lock_guard use?

RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization).

